<tr><td bgcolor="#3F403F" width="98%" class="cheader"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></td><td bgcolor="3F403F" valign="top" align="right" width="22"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/topcorner.gif" width="23" height="22" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="right"></td></tr>
<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> Top 10 Things To Know About Virtual Set 7<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.96)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=9001'>Chris "Darth Crith" Menzel</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=9001&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 20, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> For those of you not in the know, Shadows of the Empire was a multi media event created by Lucasfilms during the 90s. It is set during the period of Empire and Return of the Jedi, and tells of a war between Vader and Black Sun crime prince Xizor for the Emperors affection (sounds wrong somehow). Xizor wants to kill old Luke, and Vader wants to protect him, and bring the gangster down at the same time. Meanwhile, Dash Rander, a Han Solo wannabe, helps the rebels to locate Han, who is brought to Jabba by every-ones favorite Boba Fett.  There was no movie of course, but a book, comic series, video game, and soundtrack. It is even considered official Lucas lore. But you wanna know about the cards, so here goes…<br />
<br />
<br />
1) AGENTS ARE BACK, SON<br />
<br />
The deck type to receive the biggest push in this virtual set is certainly Agents of the Black Sun. Already boosted in set 3 with Ket Maliss (V) and his little helpers, and again in the previous set 6 with Jabbas Influence (V) by adding gangsters to the ever increasing amount of BS agents. This time around, the big boss himself enters the field, namely Prince Xizor (V). <br />
Xizor now makes smugglers, gamblers, thieves, gangsters and information brokers into BS agents (even without the objective), and also lets them draw a battle destiny, if unable to otherwise. Because of this alone, I am sure even lame guys like Ree Yees will have a cow (ouch). Although the Prince is immune to attrition smaller than twice the number of agents on table, you will be well advised to hide him in a vehicle, or Mauls ship (nice way to satisfy that Battle Plan and virtual Fire Power). The only bad thing to happen to him there, is that some-one cancels his game text with the Destiny 4 LS lost interrupt Choke (it kills a unique aliens game text during your control phase for remainder of turn). Xizor (V) also has the nifty ability to upload Unexpected Interruption once per turn, a destiny 2 lost interrupt from the Dagobah set, which allows you to search your reserve deck for any interrupt there (reshuffle). It is kinda a one-eyed Lott Dodd with a Tunnel Vision thing. You can of course also fetch the new virtual version, which is used to exclude a female from battle at a destiny draw of +2> ability, and adding her power to his own as a reward. Quite the womanizer, our green boy, and with Leia and Amidala being the only females, aside from a bunch of butt ugly aliens, you can guess who the usual targets will be. (yeah, I know about Mirax, but she’s in space).<br />
His own private doll toy Guri (V) now adds a destiny with him, and satisfies all battle damage and attrition. She further cannot have her forfeit reduced, comes for a cheap deploy of 3, and adds 1 to your drains on Coruscant where you have a BS agent. Coruscant is further the new place to be for Information Exchange (V), which deploys on the Imperial City, and may not be cancelled while a BS agent is there. You can also download some stuff with it (there is a list at the end of this topic), and Scum and Villainy can now deploy there instead of Jabbas Palace. As a reminder or the senile among you, if you only play with aliens, droids and independent ships, Scum (Destiny 4 JP effect) makes these deploy –1 and lets you retrieve 2 Force when initiating battle. Info Exchange is further protected by Alter from the old DSII admirals order Black Sun Fleet, which also makes your BS agents into information brokers (duh?), and lets you move one indy ship during your control phase (that’s mighty). Unfortunately, it is counter productive towards Scum, since it prevents you from retrieving Force while attacking.<br />
If there is anyone out there not yet convinced of playing the Agents of the BS objective till here, we can always add Frustration (V) to the mix, a new Destiny 3 used or lost interrupt from Dagobah, allowing you to re-order the top 3 cards you just peeked at, and take one into hand, or (as a lost version) allows you to add 5 to total battle destiny when Xizor and playmate Guri are in beddle (pun intended, what would you do with such a creation) together. You then also retrieve the bottom card of your lost pile into hand, which is usually your starting interrupt Prepared Defenses, so that you can add even one more to that total destiny with the help of its used version.. <br />
Finally, although it would be easier to list every character that is not a BS agent by now, I will list those that actually are agents. I separate them by groups (so there will be double listings, but you can easier find your gamblers or information brokers or whatever to use with certain interrupts):<br />
<br />
SMUGGLERS:<br />
Advosze (A New Hope) -> non-unique, so no good with AotBS<br />
Dr. Evazen (Premiere)<br />
Ephant Mon (Jabba&#39;s Palace)<br />
